{"warnings":{"query":{"*":"Formatting of continuation data will be changing soon. To continue using the current formatting, use the 'rawcontinue' parameter. To begin using the new format, pass an empty string for 'continue' in the initial query."}},"query":{"pages":{"12375151":{"pageid":12375151,"ns":0,"title":"Brain Drain (comics)","revisions":[{"contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Notability|date=March 2014}}\n{{Superherobox| <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\nimage=[[Image:BrainDrain.jpg|250px]]\n|caption=''Brain Drain'' as featured in a panel from ''[[Invaders (comics)|Invaders]]'' #2 (Oct. 1975). Art by [[Frank Robbins]].\n|comic_color=background:#ff8080\n|character_name=Brain Drain\n|real_name=Werner Schmidt\n|species=\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''Giant Size [[Invaders (comics)|Invaders]]'' #1 (June 1975) (''' First mentioned''')\n<br>''Invaders'' #2 (Oct. 1975) ('''Appearance''')\n|creators=[[Roy Thomas]] and [[Frank Robbins]]\n|alliance_color=background:#c0c0ff\n|alliances=[[Omega Flight]]\n|aliases=\n|powers=Mind control, robot body\n|}}\n\n'''Brain Drain''' is a [[fictional character]] that appears in [[comic book]]s published by [[Marvel Comics]]. The character first appears in ''[[Invaders (comics)|Invaders]]'' #2 (Oct. 1975) and was created by writer [[Roy Thomas]] and artist [[Frank Robbins]].\n\n==Fictional character biography==\n'''Werner Schmidt''' first appears as Brain Drain in the title ''[[Invaders (comics)|Invaders]]'', leading a group of beings claiming to be [[Continental Germanic mythology|Teutonic]] [[gods]] against the [[World War II]] [[superhero]] team the ''Invaders''. Brain Drain recounts in [[Flashback (narrative)|flashback]] his origin to [[Captain America]], explaining how a falling [[meteorite]] all but killed him. The ''meteorite'' was in fact a [[spacecraft|spaceship]], with the four [[Extraterrestrial life|alien]] inhabitants saving Schmidt's [[human brain|brain]] and [[human eye|eye]]s and placing them in a [[robot]] form. With his [[Neural oscillation|brain waves]] heightened during the process, Schmidt dubs himself ''Brain Drain'' and taking mental control of the aliens - which he calls \"Star Gods\" - renames them after old [[Germany|German]] gods: [[Donar]], Log, [[Froh]], and [[Brunnhilde]]. When Brunnhilde is released, she taunts Brain Drain into committing [[suicide]] in a vat of [[chemical]]s, which destroy the characters. The Invaders escape as the aliens then destroy themselves and the installation.<ref>''Invaders'' # 1 - 2 (Aug. & Oct. 1975)</ref>\n\nThe character's is mentioned by fellow [[Nazi]] villain the [[Red Skull]] in the title ''[[Marvel Premiere]]'',<ref>''Marvel Premiere'' #30 (June 1976)</ref> and reappears in a two part story in the title ''[[Marvel Two-In-One]]'', and together with Nazi allies [[Master Man (Marvel Comics)|Master Man]], [[U-Man]] and ''Skyshark'' plans to [[sabotage]] [[New York City]] with a new super weapon. The plan, however, is foiled by [[time travel]]ling [[Fantastic Four]] member the [[Thing (comics)|Thing]] and the [[Liberty Legion]].<ref>''Marvel Two-in-One'' Annual #1 (Jan. 1976) & ''Marvel Two-In-One'' #20 (Oct. 1976)</ref>\n\nThe title ''[[Alpha Flight]]'' reveals that Brain Drain's brain casing is apparently lost in the [[snow]] below a [[mountain]] for decades, and is rescued after taking mental control of a nearby [[hiker]]. The character allies himself with the [[Master of the World (comics)|Master]], a perennial foe of the superhero team ''Alpha Flight''. Joining the Master's team [[Omega Flight]] in a new robot body, Brain Drain and other villains battle the heroes on several occasions, before finally being defeated.<ref>''Alpha Flight'' #108 (May 1992); #110 - 112 (July - Sep. 1992) & #129 - 130 (Feb. - March 1994)</ref>\n\nBrain Drain is mentioned in the [[One-shot (comics)|one shot]] ''Miss America Comics 70th Anniversary Special'', as heroine [[Miss America (comics)|Miss America]] believes the character to be the mastermind behind a Nazi plan.<ref>''Miss America Comics 70th Anniversary Special'' (Aug. 2009)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Marvunapp|http://www.marvunapp.com/Appendix4/braindrain.htm|Brain Drain}}\n* [http://www.alphaflight.net/alphanex/index.php?title=Brain_Drain '''AlphaFlight.Net''' Alphanex Entry on - Brain Drain]\n\n{{Invaders}}\n\n[[Category:Characters created by Roy Thomas]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1975]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics supervillains]]\n[[Category:Nazis in comic book fiction]]\n\n\n{{Marvel-villain-stub}}"}]}}}}